CMSC320 Uber Trends NYC Final Project

Rohan Kumar, Ryan Lam, Emmanuel Benyam

Concern of our study:

Joining Uber’s extensive club of drivers seems as simple as get a car, get the app and get paid. Although this industry and life changing application creates a quick and convenient opportunity to generate revenue, the process itself isn’t without it’s faults. People that have joined Uber have voiced their experiences and highlight the problem of extensive wait time between customers. Others may have issues of planning out adequate times for driving for Uber due to other job or life constraints.

How we will conduct research:

For our study, we’ve decided to focus our attention on one extremely popular area for Uber in the United States, New York City. We set out to study the trends of Uber pickups that occurred within New York City from January 2015 to June 2015 under various conditions such as location, time of day, day of the week, and various atmospheric conditions. By doing so, we hope to understand an average 24 hour day with Uber and conclude any trends that may assist drivers in being more successful and efficient with their routes. The purpose of this research is to demonstrate to those who want to join Uber as drivers, or current Uber drivers, what conditions may affect their daily lives and understand if working for Uber is worth the investment, time and in general if it corresponds with their schedules.

In order to use this data, we needed to parse some columns into usable data types. The date is one of the most important columns that we needed to convert into a POSTIXct class from a chr class. 1.2 Snowfall Versus Uber Pickups

uber_data %>%
  group_by(Snow_Depth = floor(`Snow Depth`)) %>%
  summarize(NumPickups=sum(`No. of Pickups`)) %>%
  ggplot(mapping=aes(x=Snow_Depth, y=NumPickups)) + 
  geom_bar(stat="identity", color="blue", fill="white") +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::comma)

In order to get this graph, we will need a pipeline. We first read in our uber_data dataframe and immediately use the group_by method. The group_by method is useful for grouping columns within a dataframe based on certain conditions. In this case, we grouped by the snow depth and took the floor of the values in order to get more organized data. This splits up the data by snow depth.

We then pipe the results into a summarize method which summarizes the number of pickups based on our group_by that we used one line above. The way we used this method was to sum up pick ups based on the different snow depth values. When printed, we will see the x value as snow fall and y values of the sum of all pickups based on snowfall values.

The goal of this plot is to see if there is some sort of correlation between snow depth and number of pickups. From looking at the plot, there is no straight-forward pattern on how snow affects the number of pick ups.

This is due to the fact that most days in New York are not snowing so it makes sense that there is over 10,000,000 pick ups when there were 0 inches of snowfall. What was surprising was a higher rate for when snowfall was around 8 inches. This could be explained by people not wanting to walk to their destinations due to the heavy snow. It can also be explained by the increase of uber uses due to the holiday season. Around Christmas and New years, it is in the middle of winter which might explain why more people need to call Ubers in order to meet up with friend’s and family for parties/events.

Our initial hypothesis was that there would be a higher number of Uber pickups that occurred in the months of January to March due to increasing weather that may encourage people to use Uber. However, based on the diagram above, we noticed that there was a positive correlation between the number of pickups and time of the year with a peak in June. 1.5 Number of Pickups based on Varying Temperatures Per Month

uber_data <- uber_data %>%
    mutate(TempBreak=cut(Temperature, breaks=10))

uber_data %>%
  group_by(Month=floor_date(FullDate, "month"), TempBreak) %>%
  summarize(NumPickups=sum(`No. of Pickups`)) %>%
  ggplot(mapping=aes(x=Month, y=NumPickups)) + facet_grid(TempBreak~., scales = "free") + geom_point() + geom_smooth(method=lm) + scale_y_continuous(labels = function(x) format(x, scientific = FALSE)) + labs(y="Number of Pickups")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

Based on the results of the monthly Uber activity, we wanted to see whether temperature had an effect on the number of pickups that occurred. We hypothesized that extreme temperatures on either end of the spectrum would show higher activity in Uber rides. We created a scale for the temperatures that breaks it down into ranges of 10 degrees and looked at the number of pickups per month based on those temperature ranges. In conclusion, our hypothesis was correct and showed the highest Uber activity in both extremes of temperature, however, the information we received wasn’t adequate to determine any massive correlation between temperature and Uber activity.

1.6 Number of Pickups based on Visibility

uber_data %>%
  group_by(VisibilityCut=cut(Visibility, breaks = 4), Month=floor_date(FullDate, "month")) %>%
  summarize(NumPickups=sum(`No. of Pickups`)) %>%
  ggplot(mapping=aes(x = Month, y = NumPickups, fill = VisibilityCut)) + geom_bar(stat = "identity",position=position_dodge())+ scale_y_continuous(labels = function(x) format(x, scientific = FALSE))

This plot gets into the understanding of visibility and its relationship with the number of pickups. There are 4 different colors each representing different amounts of visibility. Furthermore, the data is also split into months of the year - with each month showing its own amounts of visibility.

To understand what this plot represents and provides us it is important to understand what “visibility” means in this context. Visibility is the amount of miles you can see ahead. This means that a higher visibility rating means it it less foggy and there is less precipitation.The plot reveals that there are more pickups when visibilities are higher as the “7.5,10” group has overwhelmingly larger numbers indicating that there are more business transactions going on on less foggy days.

2.1 Number of Pick ups Versus Holiday

uber_data %>%
  group_by(Month=floor_date(FullDate, "month"), Holiday) %>%
  summarize(NumPickups=sum(`No. of Pickups`)) %>%
  ggplot(uber_data, mapping=aes(x = Month, y = NumPickups, fill = Holiday)) + geom_bar(stat = "identity", position=position_dodge()) + scale_y_continuous(labels = function(x) format(x, scientific = FALSE)) + scale_fill_manual(values = cbp2)

This plot shows the number of uber pick ups based on holidays versus non-holidays. We expected there to be a large influx during the holidays but from looking at this graph, we can see that there is no clear corrleation between holidays versus non-holidays.

The way we plotted this was by using a pipeline. We first used the group_by method and split it by month. Our dataset has a yes/no column that indicates whether or not a day is a holiday or not. We used this parameter to group the dates that were a holiday versus those that were not. We then used the summarize method to obtain the number of pick ups for holidays and non holidays. Lastly, we used the ggplot function to plot the graph out.

Although this graph does not show any correlation, it is useful since it lets us know that holidays do not affect the number of pick ups positively or negatively. A better way to approach this if there was some sort of correlation is to standarize the data and see percent increases instead of raw sums.

2.2 Number of Pickups Based on Month and 4 Hour Spans Throughout the Day

uber_data %>%
  group_by(TimeCut=cut(Time_Dbl, breaks = 4), Month=floor_date(FullDate, "month")) %>%
  summarize(NumPickups=sum(`No. of Pickups`)) %>%
  ggplot(mapping=aes(x = Month, y = NumPickups, fill = TimeCut)) + geom_bar(stat = "identity",position=position_dodge())+ scale_y_continuous(labels = function(x) format(x, scientific = FALSE))

The plot above graphs the amount of pickups recorded for each month based on the time of day. There are four colors used when plotting each representing a different 6 hour time period of the day. For example, the last time period (in purple) spans the hours of 6,7,8,9,10 and 11 pm. We did not exactly predict a general trend among the different times of day. There was not much reason to speculate that one time of day would be more busier than the other, however, our graph reveals a different story. For each month graphed it appears that as the day progresses, more pickups occur. For each month, the first time period has the least amount of pickups, the second time period has more than that, and so on with the last time period having the most. Furthermore, as the months progress, we see the same trend and more of a gap between the last and first time period. We hypothesize that this is in part due to the sun being out longer as the months go by, yet we cannot fully be sure. Nonetheless, we clearly see that there is more business for Uber later in the day.

The main relationship we were looking for was weekdays versus weekends, especially in the summer months which showed higher Uber activity overall. Based on the results of this graph, we noticed that Saturday is consistently one of the days with the highest Uber activity whereas Monday was consistently one of the lowest. 2.4 Box and Whisker Plot, Number of Pickups Versus Weekday

uber_data$Weekdays <- as.Date(uber_data$Date)
uber_data$Weekdays <- weekdays(uber_data$Weekdays)
uber_data %>%
  group_by(Weekdays, `No. of Pickups`) %>%
  summarize(NumPickups=sum(`No. of Pickups`)) %>%
  ggplot(uber_data, mapping=aes(x = Weekdays, y = NumPickups, fill=Weekdays)) + geom_boxplot() + scale_y_continuous()

This is a box and whisker plot of the number of pick ups based on weekdays. The reason we chose to use this plot is because it gives us useful values of measure of central tendency that tells us about our data. For example, we can see the the median number of pick ups is relatively the same across any week day but the upper quartile changes more drastically than the median. We can also see the max values for each day which differs throughout each day. This change in maximums can possibly explain the changes in the upper quartile. For example, the upper quartile is significantly lower on Monday than it is on Friday and when we look at the maximum values for Friday, we can see that it is significantly higher than that of Monday. By using this plot and the previous plot from 2.3, we can see that Thursdays are the most consistent for number of ubers.

3.2 Pickup per Hour Distributions by Borough

uber_data %>%
  group_by(Time_Dbl, `No. of Pickups`, Borough) %>%
  summarize(NumPickups=sum(`No. of Pickups`)) %>%
  ggplot(subset(uber_data, !is.na(Borough)), mapping=aes(NumPickups)) +
  geom_histogram(mapping=aes(fill = Borough), bins = 40) +
  scale_x_sqrt() +
  facet_wrap(~ Borough, ncol = 2, scales = 'free') +
  labs(title = 'Pickups per hour distribution by borough', 
  x = 'Pickups per hour', y = 'Count') +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 22, hjust = 0.5), 
  legend.position = 'none', axis.title = element_text(size = 16))

This graph was utilized to see if Uber drivers could maximize profits by being active in different boroughs throughout the course of a day. We had come to a hypothesis that doing so wouldn’t be beneficial due to the issue of time wasted traveling between two boroughs as well as the additional cost of gas required to make that extra trip. Based on the results of the graph, we saw that almost every borough, besides EWR and Staten Island, had peak activity around midday. Staten Island and EWR, on the other hand, had the most activity early in the day (around midnight to 1 AM). In conclusion, we deduced that it isn’t cost efficient to travel to different boroughs throughout the course of the day as Bronx, Brooklyn, Manhattan and Queens all have peak activity around midday with a higher number of pickups than Staten Island and EWR. The pickups that fell into the category of “NA” were Uber pickups that occurred within the city but not within the geographical coordinates of a borough or were too vague to be generalized to a borough.

3.3 Regression Model Number of Pickups vs Month by Weekdays

uber_data$Weekdays <- as.Date(uber_data$Date)
uber_data$Weekdays <- weekdays(uber_data$Weekdays)

uber_data %>%
  group_by(Month=floor_date(FullDate, "month"), Weekdays) %>%
  summarize(NumPickups=sum(`No. of Pickups`)) %>%
  ggplot(uber_data, mapping=aes(x = Month, y = NumPickups, fill = Weekdays, color = Weekdays)) + geom_point() + scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::comma) + scale_fill_manual(values = cbp2) + geom_smooth(method = lm, aes(fill=Weekdays), se=FALSE, fullrange=TRUE)
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

This plot shows number of pick ups based on the month by which week day. There are 5 different colored points on this plot and each one represents a different week day. As seen above, we can see the total number of pick ups on Saturday in the month of January was right below 400,000.

To make this plot, we first created a pipe with uber_data. We used the group_by function first and grouped by Month and weekday. This splits our data up based on the month and weekday of the data. We then used a summarize function in order to figure out the amount of pick ups per day per month which we used to plot. Next, we used the ggplot function to create the actual plot. The first parameter indicates our dataset which is uber_data. The next parameter is the aesthetics parameter which has many other parameters within. The most important 2 are the x and y parameters which indicate what values to use for the x and y coordinate. The next parameter that we used was fill which fills the color of the lines based on the weekday.

After this, we wanted physical points on the plot so we added the ’+ geom_point()" parameter. The y axis was in scientific notation which is hard to read so the next parameter is used to place commas in the numerical values. The next parameter just indicates what color range to use with the graphs to make it more visually pleasing. The last parameter is the most important part where we implement a linear regression method which is based on the number of pick ups as well as the week day. On the plot, the linear line is fitted based on the value. This regression shows that the number of pick ups steadily increases for each week day as the month increases.

3.4 Number of Pickups vs Time Regression

library(tidyr)

ggplot(uber_data, aes(Time_Dbl, `No. of Pickups`)) + geom_jitter(alpha = 0.2) +
  geom_smooth()
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'gam' and formula 'y ~ s(x, bs = "cs")'

This graph visualizes the linear regression that we modeled based on number of pickups and time of day. We concluded that time of day has the largest quantifiable relationship with number of pickups. The trend that we noticed was that early mornings, such as late night past midnight, and evenings, such as after work, had the highest activity for Uber drivers. The time of day that had the lowest Uber driver activity was around 3-5 AM which makes sense as most people are asleep by that time. Additionally, there seems to be an upward trend that begins at 5-6 AM and continues until 11 AM which may indicate surges based on people commuting to work.

Conclusion

Based on our various hypotheses throughout the course of this tutorial, we concluded that time of day is the most prominent quantifiable variable that affects the number of pickups for Uber drivers. For people that are considering joining the force of Uber drivers, or current Uber drivers looking to maximize their time and effort, this tutorial contains a plethora of information that you may use to plan your occupational life out with Uber. We have put together a brief summary that may help you understand this experiment and its results and how you can use this information at your disposal.

If your primary concern in terms of Uber activity is location, then Manhattan is the borough that consistently has the highest number of pickups across the board.

If you are looking to work Uber part time or during other times of the day, then late at night (midnight to 2 AM) and anywhere from 5 PM to 10 PM shows the highest activity across the boroughs.

If you are trying to see what days of the week are the most promising, then Friday and Saturday have the most activity for the weekends and, for weekdays, Thursday has the most activity.

If you are trying to see if holidays have a major impact on the Uber activity in NYC, we deduced that there’s no positive correlation between holidays from work and Uber activity (at least for the first 6 months of the year).

If you are trying to see what atmospheric and weather conditions are most beneficial, we deduced that extremely hot or extremely cold days have the most activity. Additionally, days that have high levels of precipitation show more activity amongst Uber drivers but nothing that is too promising based on those conditions.
